  "prompt": "How does stereo differ from mono?",
  "response": "Stereo and mono refer to two different types of audio signal processing, and they differ primarily in how they handle channels and spatial audio information.\n\nMono, short for monophonic sound, uses a single audio channel. This means that all sound, regardless of its source, is combined into one channel and played through one speaker or both speakers simultaneously, without any spatial differentiation. Mono sound is centralized and does not provide any sense of direction or placement of the audio sources within the listening environment.\n\nStereo, short for stereophonic sound, uses two audio channels \u2013 typically referred to as the left and right channels. These channels can carry different audio signals, which allows stereo sound to create the illusion of spatial distribution of audio sources. When you listen to stereo sound, you can perceive where different sounds are coming from within the stereo field; for example, a guitar might sound like it is coming from the left side, while a piano might sound like it's more to the right. This spatial differentiation enhances the listening experience by adding depth and dimension to the audio.\n\nIn summary, mono sound combines all audio into a single channel, while stereo sound uses two channels to create a more immersive and directional audio experience.",
